      DWAC S-4
   =20
 =20
Donald Trump=E2=80=99s social media=C2=A0company, Trump Media & Technology =
Group Corp., which runs the =E2=80=9CTruth Social=E2=80=9D app,=C2=A0plans =
to go public by merging with a special purpose acquisition company called D=
igital World Acquisition Corp., raising  something like $1.3 billion. Today=
 TMTG and DWAG filed the registration statement for their merger, a key ste=
p in actually making it happen.=C2=A0You can read it =E2=80=94=C2=A0here it=
 is =E2=80=94=C2=A0and of course I will discuss it, because it is funny and=
 because that is what I do for a living. But in a sense there is no=C2=A0po=
int=C2=A0in reading it. It will not tell you much about TMTG=E2=80=99s busi=
ness, because TMTG doesn=E2=80=99t have much of a business. Sure it has no =
real revenue,[1] but it also has almost no=C2=A0expenses. In 2021 (the only=
 period for which it has=C2=A0financial statements), TMTG had total operati=
ng expenses of about $6.4 million, consisting mainly of pay and expenses fo=
r its =E2=80=9Capproximately 40 full-time employees.=E2=80=9D Twitter Inc.,=
 a real social media company that TMTG supposedly competes with, spent roug=
hly twice that much=C2=A0each day=C2=A0on operating expenses last quarter.H=
ere is TMTG=E2=80=99s plan for eventually making money:TMTG intends to have=
 a sales force and sales support staff that is focused on attracting and re=
taining advertisers. TMTG expects that its sales force and sales support st=
aff will assist advertisers throughout the advertising campaign cycle, from=
=C2=A0pre-purchase=C2=A0decision making to real-time optimizations as they =
utilize TMTG=E2=80=99s campaign management tools, and to post-campaign anal=
ytics reports to assess the effectiveness of their advertising campaigns.TM=
TG expects that its marketing campaigns will focus on celebrating and highl=
ighting the voices of all people who make TruthSocial unique. TMTG believes=
 advertisers could eventually be attracted to a platform that encourages fr=
ee and open debate among all users rather than to a platform that seeks to =
silence diverse perspectives=E2=80=94including views held by large swaths o=
f Americans.=E2=80=9COne day, we will try to=C2=A0sell ads.=E2=80=9D Great!=
 When?TMTG may begin to generate revenue from the TruthSocial platform as e=
arly as 2023. However, TMTG may elect to defer certain revenue driving acti=
vities to optimize the platform=E2=80=99s user experience and active user g=
rowth. TMTG views TruthSocial active user growth as a critical driver of lo=
ng-term value and may prioritize the TruthSocial user experience over short=
-term revenue goals.Sure, that makes sense; first you grow your user base a=
nd then you monetize. How many active users does Truth Social have, anyway?=
 Incredibly, the paragraph I quoted above is the only occurrence=C2=A0of th=
e phrase =E2=80=9Cactive user=E2=80=9D in the entire prospectus. The metric=
 that most social media companies emphasize =E2=80=94=C2=A0their daily or m=
onthly active user numbers =E2=80=94=C2=A0simply doesn=E2=80=99t appear. TM=
TG did not think it was worth mentioning how many people use=C2=A0Truth Soc=
ial.Now. This is a SPAC deal. Here is where I have to say some traditional =
things about SPACs. When a private company wants to go public these days, i=
t can choose to either (1) do a standard initial public offering or (2) mer=
ge with a SPAC. SPACs have advantages and disadvantages compared to IPOs, b=
ut often the most salient advantage is that a company going public by a SPA=
C merger can include=C2=A0projections of future income=C2=A0in its prospect=
us, while that is more or less forbidden in a regular IPO. (Not really: It=
=E2=80=99s just that, if the projections in an IPO prospectus are wrong, yo=
u can get sued for fraud, while if the projections in a SPAC merger prospec=
tus are wrong you have a =E2=80=9Csafe harbor=E2=80=9D from liability.[2]) =
Thus if you are, say, a pre-revenue electric-vehicle company, a SPAC will b=
e more attractive than an IPO: An IPO prospectus will just focus on your hi=
storical losses, while a SPAC prospectus can focus on your future profits. =
If the projections turn out to be wrong, well, stuff happens.But this tradi=
tional SPAC theory does not apply to TMTG, for two reasons. The first reaso=
n is that=C2=A0the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission has announced th=
at  it=E2=80=99s going to change the rules to make it just as risky to incl=
ude projections in a SPAC as in an IPO. (=E2=80=9COn March 30, 2022, the SE=
C issued proposed rules ... effectively limiting the use of projections in =
SEC filings in connection with proposed business combination transactions,=
=E2=80=9D says a risk factor in the DWAC prospectus.) So TMTG can=E2=80=99t=
 market itself based on optimistic projections of future user growth and re=
venue.The second reason is that nobody cares about TMTG=E2=80=99s projectio=
ns, nobody is valuing TMTG on some multiple of future cash flow or revenue =
or even users, nobody is doing any sort of financial modeling at all, the b=
usiness is not the point, so there=E2=80=99s no reason to include any proje=
ctions. When TMTG and DWAC announced their deal last October,  I wrote:Why =
would you think Trump Thing, a company with no product and no revenue, is w=
orth $1.7 billion? Are you looking at the wildly optimistic projections of =
future revenue in the investor presentation? No you certainly are not! The =
initial SEC filing doesn=E2=80=99t include an investor presentation, but th=
ere is a =E2=80=9CCompany Overview=E2=80=9D deck on Trump Thing=E2=80=99s w=
ebsite, and, fun fact, there is not a single dollar sign in the whole deck.=
 There is no financial analysis, no sources and uses of funds for the deal,=
 no capital structure, and certainly no projections of future revenue.=C2=
=A0Today=E2=80=99s prospectus also does not include any projections of reve=
nue, user growth or anything else.[3] In fact it goes out of its way to say=
 that any projections of TMTG=E2=80=99s future financial performance are be=
side the point:In connection with Digital World=E2=80=99s review of the Bus=
iness Combination, TMTG provided Digital World=E2=80=99s management with it=
s internal financial analysis model. Although Digital World=E2=80=99s board=
 received certain financial projections included in TMTG=E2=80=99s financia=
l model, it did not rely on these financial projections as a determinative =
factor in its decision to enter into the Business Combination Agreement.In =
deciding to take TMTG public, DWAC =E2=80=94=C2=A0the SPAC here =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0did get financial projections from TMTG, but it promptly threw them i=
n the garbage.[4] Here is the process that DWAC did use in trying to=C2=A0v=
alue TMTG:Digital World=E2=80=99s management, in consultation with EF Hutto=
n, reviewed certain financial and operating information of Trading Comparab=
les, particularly, similar social media, content production and distributio=
n, and=C2=A0media companies around the world. The selected companies includ=
ed a group of companies operating in various global markets, including, amo=
