rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">plan for eventually maki=
ng money</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TMTG intends to h=
ave a sales force and sales support staff that is focused on attracting and=
 retaining advertisers. TMTG expects that its sales force and sales support=
 staff will assist advertisers throughout the advertising campaign cycle, f=
rom=C2=A0pre-purchase=C2=A0decision making to real-time optimizations as th=
ey utilize TMTG=E2=80=99s campaign management tools, and to post-campaign a=
nalytics reports to assess the effectiveness of their advertising campaigns=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TMTG expects that its marketing campaigns=
 will focus on celebrating and highlighting the voices of all people who ma=
ke TruthSocial unique. TMTG believes advertisers could eventually be attrac=
ted to a platform that encourages free and open debate among all users rath=
er than to a platform that seeks to silence diverse perspectives=E2=80=94in=
cluding views held by large swaths of Americans.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9COne day, we will try to=C2=A0sell ads.=E2=80=
=9D Great! When?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TMTG may begin=
 to generate revenue from the TruthSocial platform as early as 2023. Howeve=
r, TMTG may elect to defer certain revenue driving activities to optimize t=
he platform=E2=80=99s user experience and active user growth. TMTG views Tr=
uthSocial active user growth as a critical driver of long-term value and ma=
y prioritize the TruthSocial user experience over short-term revenue goals.=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure, that makes sense; first=
 you grow your user base and then you monetize. How many active users does =
Truth Social have, anyway? Incredibly, the paragraph I quoted above is the =
only occurrence=C2=A0of the phrase =E2=80=9Cactive user=E2=80=9D in the ent=
ire prospectus. The metric that most social media companies emphasize =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0their daily or monthly active user numbers =E2=80=94=C2=A0simpl=
y doesn=E2=80=99t appear. TMTG did not think it was worth mentioning how ma=
ny people use=C2=A0Truth Social.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now. This =
is a SPAC deal. Here is where I have to say some traditional things about S=
PACs. When a private company wants to go public these days, it can choose t=
o either (1) do a standard initial public offering or (2) merge with a SPAC=
. SPACs have advantages and disadvantages compared to IPOs, but often the m=
ost salient advantage is that a company going public by a SPAC merger can i=
nclude=C2=A0<em>projections of future income</em>=C2=A0in its prospectus, w=
hile that is more or less forbidden in a regular IPO. (Not really: It=E2=80=
=99s just that, if the projections in an IPO prospectus are <em>wrong</em>,=
 you can get sued for fraud, while if the projections in a SPAC merger pros=
pectus are wrong you have a =E2=80=9Csafe harbor=E2=80=9D from liability.[2=
]) Thus if you are, say, a pre-revenue electric-vehicle company, a SPAC wil=
l be more attractive than an IPO: An IPO prospectus will just focus on your=
 historical losses, while a SPAC prospectus can focus on your future profit=
s. If the projections turn out to be wrong, well, stuff happens.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this traditional SPAC theory does not apply to TM=
TG, for two reasons. The first reason is that=C2=A0the U.S. Securities and =
Exchange Commission has announced that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/27733329.285614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMzEvdGhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pbmctZm9yLXNwYWNzP2Ntc=
GlkPUJCRDA1MTYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdz=
bGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBa4719420" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> it=E2=80=99s going to change the rules</a> =
to make it just as risky to include projections in a SPAC as in an IPO. (=
=E2=80=9COn March 30, 2022, the SEC issued proposed rules ... effectively l=
imiting the use of projections in SEC filings in connection with proposed b=
usiness combination transactions,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/27733329.285614/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaX=
Zlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDk2MzUvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyMTUwODAxL2QyMjYyMDVkczQuaHRtI=
3JvbTIyNjIwNV8xMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd919b3d1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says a risk fa=
ctor</a> in the DWAC prospectus.) So TMTG can=E2=80=99t market itself based=
 on optimistic projections of future user growth and revenue.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second reason is that nobody cares about TMTG=E2=
=80=99s projections, nobody is valuing TMTG on some multiple of future cash=
 flow or revenue or even users, nobody is doing any sort of financial model=
ing at all, the business is not the point, so there=E2=80=99s no reason to =
include any projections. When TMTG and DWAC announced their deal last Octob=
er, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27733329.28561=
4/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMjEvb=
WF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1kb25hbGQtdHJ1bXAtZG9lcy1hLXNwYWM_Y21waWQ9=
